nian with energies in a narrow interval {\textbackslash}(\{[E, E+ {\textbackslash}delta E]\}{\textbackslash})) and most orthonormal bases of {\textbackslash}(\{{\textbackslash}mathcal \{H\}\_\{2\}\}{\textbackslash}), {\textbackslash}(\{{\textbackslash}mu\_\{1\}\}{\textbackslash}) is close to {\textbackslash}(\{GAP({\textbackslash}rm \{tr\}\_\{2\} {\textbackslash}rho\_\{mc\})\}{\textbackslash}) with {\textbackslash}(\{{\textbackslash}rho\_\{mc\}\}{\textbackslash}) the normalized projection to the microcanonical subspace. In particular, if the coupling between the system and the environment is weak, then {\textbackslash}(\{{\textbackslash}mu\_\{1\}\}{\textbackslash}) is close to {\textbackslash}(\{GAP({\textbackslash}rho\_{\textbackslash}beta)\}{\textbackslash}) with {\textbackslash}(\{{\textbackslash}rho\_{\textbackslash}beta\}{\textbackslash}) the canonical density matrix on {\textbackslash}(\{{\textbackslash}mathcal \{H\}\_\{1\}\}{\textbackslash}) at inverse temperature {\textbackslash}(\{{\textbackslash}beta={\textbackslash}beta(E)\}{\textbackslash}). This provides the mathematical justification of our claim in Goldstein et al. (J Stat Phys 125: 1193--1221, 2006) that GAP measures describe the thermal equilibrium distribution of the wave function.},
