  abstract = {In this paper, we reveal that the unitary freedom in ensemble of pure states with a given state and the unitary freedom in operator-sum representation for a given channel are no longer valid for infinite-dimensional systems. The replacements of them are, respectively, the contractive freedom in ensemble and the contractive freedom in operator-sum representation. Precisely, we show that, (1) two ensembles {\textbackslash}({\textbackslash}\{{\textbar}{\textbackslash}phi \_i{\textbackslash}rangle , p\_i{\textbackslash}\}{\textbackslash}) and {\textbackslash}({\textbackslash}\{{\textbar}{\textbackslash}psi \_j{\textbackslash}rangle , q\_j{\textbackslash}\}{\textbackslash}) determine the same state if and only if there exists some contractive matrix {\textbackslash}(V=(v\_\{ij\}){\textbackslash}) such that {\textbackslash}({\textbackslash}sqrt\{p\_i\}{\textbar}{\textbackslash}phi \_i{\textbackslash}rangle ={\textbackslash}sum \_j v\_\{ij\}{\textbackslash}sqrt\{q\_j\}{\textbar}{\textbackslash}psi \_j{\textbackslash}rangle {\textbackslash}) for each i; (2) two sequences {\textbackslash}({\textbackslash}\{A\_i{\textbackslash}\}{\textbackslash}) and {\textbackslash}({\textbackslash}\{B\_j{\textbackslash}\}{\textbackslash}) of Kraus operators in operator-sum representations determine the same quantum channel if and only if there exists some contractive matrix {\textbackslash}(V=(v\_\{ij\}){\textbackslash}) such that {\textbackslash}(A\_i={\textbackslash}sum \_jv\_\{ij\}B\_j{\textbackslash}) for each i. All possible quantum ensembles of pure states with any given state and all possible operator-sum representations of any given channel are described.},
